canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103732","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103732"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 27-year-old man presents after being retrieved from a motor vehicle crash in which he was the restrained driver hit by a side impact from another vehicle failing to stop at traffic lights.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn primary survey, the patient is fully responsive, conscious, alert, oriented and complaining of right-sided chest pain and shortness of breath. His airway is clear, his respiratory rate is 20 and his SpO2 is 96% on a face mask at a delivery rate of 6L/min. His trachea is midline and he is tender over his right chest laterally, with pain limiting inspiration. His blood pressure is 120/60 mmHg and pulse 100/min.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA CT scan is performed (Images 1, 2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Apart from pain relief, which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Central venous access line","Underwater seal chest drain","Heimlich valve","Pericardial aspiration","Chest wall binder"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has a fairly sizeable haemopneumothorax and this needs to be drained as soon as possible. This is done with a \u003Cstrong\u003Echest\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Edrain\u003C/strong\u003E with an underwater seal. In 70-80% of patients, this is successful treatment alone; however, in some patients, escalation of treatment with emergency thoracotomy may be required. This is particularly in patients with massive haemothorax; defined as draining \u0026gt;1000mL initially, or \u0026gt;200mL/hr over 2-4 hours.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDepending on this patients haemoglobin and haemodynamic stability, they may also need a blood transfusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA central venous line would not be indicated in this patient, as it is unlikely to help treat his haemothorax.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHeimlich valve is a one way valve that is in the treatment of pneumothorax; however, it would not be so helpful in the treatment of haemothorax, where a drainage tube would need to be inserted and the blood risks blocking the valve.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA pericardial aspiration would be appropriate in cardiac tamponade, which presents with Beck\u0027s triad; muffled heart sounds, hypotension, and jugular venous distension. Whilst the CT suggests that the patient might have a small pericardial effusion, it is not of significant enough size to produce any tamponade effect. If it does eventually need to be aspirated, that would be of secondary importance to the management of the haemopneumothorax.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA chest wall binder is used in patients who have three or more acutely displaced rib fractures or flail chest (two or more contiguous ribs fractured in two or more places), particularly when they fail conservative treatment. According to this, this patient does not appear to have any indication for a chest wall binder. Secondly, even if they did, treatment of this patient\u0027s haemothorax is far more urgent, and should be performed prior to consideration of a chest wall binder for stabilisation of rib fractures.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Underwater seal chest drain is the first-line treatment in haemothorax","If patient\u0027s with haemothorax drain \u003E1500mL or \u003E200mL/hr for 2 hours, consideration of surgical thoracotomy is warranted"],"references":["de Campos JRM, White TW. Chest wall stabilization in trauma patients: why, when, and how? J Thorac Dis. 2018 Apr;10(Suppl 8):S951-S962. doi: 10.21037/jtd.2018.04.69. PMID: 29744222; PMCID: PMC5934118.","Broderick SR. Hemothorax: Etiology, diagnosis, and management. Thorac Surg Clin. 2013 Feb;23(1):89-96, vi-vii. doi: 10.1016/j.thorsurg.2012.10.003. Epub 2012 Nov 3. PMID: 23206720.","Boersma WG, Stigt JA, Smit HJ. Treatment of haemothorax. Respir Med. 2010 Nov;104(11):1583-7. doi: 10.1016/j.rmed.2010.08.006. PMID: 20817498."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86153"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1054"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18441"},{"type":"media","id":"18442"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18441","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18441"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1dae1345-b675-43dc-934d-cb3202e060bd.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1dae1345-b675-43dc-934d-cb3202e060bd.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":538,"height":440}},{"type":"media","id":"18442","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18442"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e8a7403a-38be-4b11-93b1-bb26b63b70e4.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e8a7403a-38be-4b11-93b1-bb26b63b70e4.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":500,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86153","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86153"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-26T09:03:53+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-29T14:17:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1054"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103732"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergen